New Zero Day Announced on News: PwnCrypt Ransomware

Microsoft Defender for Endpoint Threat Hunt Portfolio Project

Project Overview

This project documents a threat hunt investigation involving a newly reported ransomware strain named PwnCrypt.

The ransomware was reported to use a PowerShell based payload to encrypt files on infected systems. The payload used AES 256 encryption and targeted specific directories, including `C:\Users\Public\Desktop`.

The known indicator of compromise was the creation of files containing `.pwncrypt` in the file name. For example, a file named `hello.txt` could become `hello.pwncrypt.txt` after encryption.

The purpose of the hunt was to determine whether PwnCrypt had entered the corporate environment, whether files were encrypted, and what process activity was responsible.

This investigation used Microsoft Defender for Endpoint telemetry and KQL queries to review:

- PwnCrypt file indicators
- Encrypted file creation
- PowerShell execution
- Execution policy bypass activity
- Malicious script execution
- Ransomware impact
- MITRE ATT&CK technique mapping
- Response and containment actions

Scenario Summary

A new ransomware strain named PwnCrypt was reported in the news.

The ransomware used a PowerShell based payload to encrypt files and prepend `.pwncrypt` into the original file extension.

The CISO was concerned that the ransomware may have spread into the corporate network because the organization had an immature security program and limited user security training.

The hunt was initiated using the known PwnCrypt file indicator:

```text
.pwncrypt
```

The investigation focused on whether files containing `pwncrypt` appeared on the target device and whether PowerShell was used to execute the ransomware payload.

