Execution Chain

| Step | Activity | Evidence |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | PwnCrypt script was introduced to the device | `pwncrypt.ps1` observed |
| 2 | PowerShell was launched | `powershell.exe` process activity |
| 3 | Execution restrictions were bypassed | `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass` observed |
| 4 | PwnCrypt payload executed | `pwncrypt.ps1` ran from `C:\ProgramData` |
| 5 | Files were encrypted | File names containing `pwncrypt` were created |

Interpretation

The investigation confirmed that the activity was not just the presence of a suspicious file. The device showed both ransomware file impact and the PowerShell execution chain used to run the ransomware payload.

The use of `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass` increased the severity because it showed that the script was run in a way that bypassed normal PowerShell execution restrictions.

Investigation Summary

The device `vme-windows-hun` showed confirmed PwnCrypt ransomware activity.

The ransomware created encrypted files containing the `.pwncrypt` indicator and was executed using PowerShell with execution policy bypass.

The activity matched the known ransomware behavior described in the scenario and required immediate containment.

Stage 5 Response

Goal

Contain the ransomware infection and prevent potential spread across the network.

Response Actions Taken

| Response Action | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Immediately isolated the system | Prevented possible ransomware spread |
| Submitted ticket for rebuild or reimage | Restored the device to a trusted state |
| Planned detection rule for `pwncrypt` | Improved future detection |
| Planned blocklist entry for `pwncrypt` | Reduced chance of repeat execution |
| Awaited management response | Allowed leadership to decide next steps |

Response Summary

The device was immediately isolated after ransomware activity was confirmed.

Because the infection involved ransomware, the best remediation path was to rebuild or reimage the system rather than attempt to trust the infected operating system.

A detection rule and blocklist entry for `pwncrypt` were planned to reduce the chance of the same ransomware activity recurring.

Recommended Security Controls

| Control | Reason |
|---|---|
| Isolate infected endpoints immediately | Prevents ransomware spread |
| Reimage infected systems | Restores the system to a trusted state |
| Block known ransomware indicators | Prevents known payloads from executing again |
| Create detection rules for `.pwncrypt` files | Improves early detection |
| Alert on PowerShell execution policy bypass | Detects suspicious script execution |
| Restrict PowerShell usage | Reduces script based attack surface |
| Monitor `C:\ProgramData` script execution | Identifies suspicious script staging |
| Improve user security training | Reduces risk of users executing malicious payloads |
| Maintain tested backups | Supports recovery after encryption events |
| Review endpoint protection configuration | Improves prevention and detection maturity |

